# Rails and mixed-stack conventions

When editing matching files, follow **convention over configuration** and keep clear boundaries between Ruby, client JS/React, and Python.

## Source of truth

Read and apply the full checklist and sections in [.cursor/skills/rails-conventions-mixed-stacks/SKILL.md](.cursor/skills/rails-conventions-mixed-stacks/SKILL.md) for:

- Thin controllers, RESTful routes, Active Record discipline, jobs vs services
- Hotwire (Stimulus/Turbo) vs React integration and API/CSRF patterns
- Python scripts or services: contracts and avoiding duplicated domain rules

## Project stack (quick)

This app uses Rails 8 with **Propshaft**, **jsbundling-rails**, **Stimulus**, and **Turbo** per `Gemfile`. Prefer those defaults before adding parallel patterns.

If a change spans Ruby and `app/javascript`, keep business rules on the server unless the UI is explicitly the owner of that behavior.
